    The Movies Dataset
    Metadata on over 45,000 movies. 26 million ratings from over 270,000 users.
    Last Updated: a year ago (Version 7)
    About this Dataset

    Context

    These files contain metadata for all 45,000 movies listed in the Full MovieLens Dataset. The dataset consists of movies released on or before July 2017. Data points include cast, crew, plot keywords, budget, revenue, posters, release dates, languages, production companies, countries, TMDB vote counts and vote averages.

    This dataset also has files containing 26 million ratings from 270,000 users for all 45,000 movies. Ratings are on a scale of 1-5 and have been obtained from the official GroupLens website.

    Content

    This dataset consists of the following files:

    movies_metadata.csv: The main Movies Metadata file. Contains information on 45,000 movies featured in the Full MovieLens dataset. Features include posters, backdrops, budget, revenue, release dates, languages, production countries and companies.

    keywords.csv: Contains the movie plot keywords for our MovieLens movies. Available in the form of a stringified JSON Object.

    credits.csv: Consists of Cast and Crew Information for all our movies. Available in the form of a stringified JSON Object.

    links.csv: The file that contains the TMDB and IMDB IDs of all the movies featured in the Full MovieLens dataset.

    links_small.csv: Contains the TMDB and IMDB IDs of a small subset of 9,000 movies of the Full Dataset.

    ratings_small.csv: The subset of 100,000 ratings from 700 users on 9,000 movies.

    The Full MovieLens Dataset consisting of 26 million ratings and 750,000 tag applications from 270,000 users on all the 45,000 movies in this dataset can be accessed here

    Acknowledgements

    This dataset is an ensemble of data collected from TMDB and GroupLens. The Movie Details, Credits and Keywords have been collected from the TMDB Open API. This product uses the TMDb API but is not endorsed or certified by TMDb. Their API also provides access to data on many additional movies, actors and actresses, crew members, and TV shows. You can try it for yourself here.

    The Movie Links and Ratings have been obtained from the Official GroupLens website. The files are a part of the dataset available here

    Inspiration

    This dataset was assembled as part of my second Capstone Project for Springboard's Data Science Career Track. I wanted to perform an extensive EDA on Movie Data to narrate the history and the story of Cinema and use this metadata in combination with MovieLens ratings to build various types of Recommender Systems.

    Both my notebooks are available as kernels with this dataset: The Story of Film and Movie Recommender Systems

    Some of the things you can do with this dataset: Predicting movie revenue and/or movie success based on a certain metric. What movies tend to get higher vote counts and vote averages on TMDB? Building Content Based and Collaborative Filtering Based Recommendation Engines.

    Hi Fabien

    Great work, one if not the most interesting notebook on datascience/movies I've seen. However I'm always a bit frustrated to see that the corpus and examples are always in the same category of movies, e.g blockbusters which are largely "industrial products", based on a recipee (= joseph campbell's man with 10 000 faces) and engineered in the forges of hollywood. In this case, I believe budget, lead actors, producer and exposure largely account for a movie "score", where as most imdb highscore in a given year will be forgotten by history in a couple of decades.
    Movie as an art form, from silent movies to corean or french new wave, require vastly different features that I'm trying to explore : a director career and stance, a favorite genre, close collaboration with editors or actors, language (I have nightmares where the beautiful poetry of Rohmer's spoken philosophy is dubbed in english :D)

    I have a couple of remarks and questions

    • Given the impact (5%) using synonyms seems overengineered. Overall as keywords are largely declarative I'm really dubious about using them efficiently. Using the script, or at the very least a wikipedia a summary, could be more efficient.

    • Removing keywords that rarely appear is a risk, as they might just be the one that carry the most meaning, or that make a movie stand appart (=> see the TF-IDF weighting methodology). Since you're trying to find a nearest neighbor, I understand the choice though

    • [QUESTION] You're using euclidian distance to measure nearest neighbors. Have you considered other distances ? I was thinking of Jaccard similarity, which I've seen employed in other studies.

    • One issue I have with scaled datasets and euclidian distance is that every dimension has the same weight. It might be interesting to determine, either by asking the user or based on his historical preferences, to determine if user pattern of choice : maybe he chooses movies by genre ? Or by lead actor ? Or by language ? Or director ? Or release year ?

    Seeing that we're both french, I'd be interested to chat a bit with you on this project but can't message you through Kaggle. Is there a way you could send me an email to stephane.rappeneau at free.fr ?

    Cheers and thanks again for this great work !

    FabienDanielKernel AuthorPosted on Version 56a year agoOptionsReply
    3

    Great comment !! Surely, you know much more about cinema than I do myself.
    I'll try to answer as best as possible the various points you address:

    • the IMDB 5000 movies database mostly contains blockbusters, and I agree with you that most of them are just variants of a same story. However, that's where the money is and this is surely why there are largely more numerous than other kind of movies (that would rely more on scenarios, actors psychology, richness of dialogues, etc ). Well, sincerely, I like (many but not all) blockbusters too !!

    • the work on synonyms was motivated by the fact that I would have suppressed the corresponding keywords, otherwise, due to their low frequency. I thus wanted to check if I could adopt a different strategy before throwing some data at garbage. However, as you point out, the impact seems rather modest and this might be overengineered indeed ! As you say, a better job could have been done using synopsis rather than a simple set of keywords: since they are limited in number, an error in assignment can have huge consequences. This was however out of the scope of that particular project where I just wanted to draw the great lines of a recommendation engine (and did not pretend to produce a viable engine).

    • for the removal of keywords, I understand your point concerning the information carrier. But in the current case, I focused on keywords usage: for a keyword to be useful, it needs to appear a sufficient number of times to reduce the distance between films. From your comment, I see that you get that point :)

    • for sure, I have binary data in the matrix and euclidean distance is definitely not the best choice: a better choice would have been Hamming distance. I did not try to perform tests on this aspect though.

    • concerning your last point, indeed, all the categories have the same weight in the distance calculation. This might not be appropriate though, since user's choice will be more surely driven by the director's choice rather than the fact the word "cat" appear in two different set of keywords this is surely a point to address to improve the recommendation engine !!

    I would be happy to discuss more on that topic (I wrote you a mail) !!

    Thanks for all that comments !!

    Gunhee ParkPosted on Latest Versiona year agoOptionsReply
    0

    Can I ask you another question?
    I'm really struggling to find why numerical features like 'budget', 'gross' and 'title_year' are not used for recommendation system?

    FabienDanielKernel AuthorPosted on Latest Versiona year agoOptionsReply
    1

    Actually, I used the title_year variable to put more weights on films that were released around the same year than the film selected by the user.

    However, I didn't use the budget or gross variables for two reasons:

    • 1$ does not worth the same all along the XXth century and you need to account for this when comparing films of different epochs.
    • in the initial database, some values in budget or gross were not converted in dollars and were still given in the initial currency.

    Hence, I agree that using these variables might prove useful but it is not straightforward to correctly include them in the engine.
